,"1261–Male":"1261–Deceased","1268–Female":"1268–Deceased","1276–1347":"1276–1347","–Male":"Deceased","1260–1322":"1260–1322","1280–1313":"1280–1313","1285–1333":"1285–1333","1234–1290":"1234–1290","1245–1283":"1245–1283","1285":"1285","1283":"1283","1261":"1261","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","8 January 1283":"8 January 1283","1347":"1347","1313":"1313","1268":"1268","1245":"1245","1234":"1234","1333":"1333","1322":"1322","1265":"1265","1276":"1276","Abt 1280":"about 1280","about 1285":"about 1285","Liverpool, Lancashire, England":"Liverpool, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Standish, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Standish, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Standish, Lancashire, England":"Standish, Lancashire, England","Ince in Makerfield, Wigan, Lancashire, England":"Wigan, Lancashire, England","Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Standish","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name from Standish (Lancashire, now part of Greater Manchester), from Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>edisc</i> ‘enclosure, enclosed park’. Standish (Gloucestershire) does not appear to have contributed towards the surname.","History: Myles Standish (<i>c.</i> 1584–1656) was a soldier of fortune, from 1620 captain of the <i>Mayflower</i> Pilgrims at Plymouth Colony. Little is known of his origins and early life, but in his will he claimed to be descended from a leading Catholic family, the Standishes of Standish, Lancashire, England. He also claimed to have been deprived of his inheritance, a claim not confirmed."],"variants":[{"name":"Standage","meanings":["English:","probably a variant of   Standish  .","in Leicestershire and Buckinghamshire, the name may alternatively be from Stanedge Grange in Hartington Nether Quarter or Stanage End in Outseats (both Derbyshire); but evidence is needed for this. The placenames derive from Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>ecg</i> ‘edge, escarpment’."]}]},{"name":"Alesia","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Another form of Alice"],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alesia Alice Standish was born in 1265, in Standish, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Jordan Standish, was 31 and her mother, Alianore, was 20. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Alfredus De Haydock. She died in 1305, in Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1265–1305":"1265–1305","1261–Male":"1261–Surnud","1268–Female":"1268–Surnud","1276–1347":"1276–1347","–Male":"Surnud","1260–1322":"1260–1322","1280–1313":"1280–1313","1285–1333":"1285–1333","1234–1290":"1234–1290","1245–1283":"1245–1283","1285":"1285","1283":"1283","1261":"1261","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","8 January 1283":"8. jaanuar 1283","1347":"1347","1313":"1313","1268":"1268","1245":"1245","1234":"1234","1333":"1333","1322":"1322","1265":"1265","1276":"1276","Abt 1280":"umbes 1280","about 1285":"umbes 1285","Liverpool, Lancashire